{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_moser_ver01/data/sn85025371/00542867322/1930091801/0724.xml":{"full_text":"The Clarke Courier\nR. N.- Dorsey, Publisher\n\nEstablished In 1800 by Capt. Wm. N.\nNelson; owned and edited by the\nlate John O. Crown and Joseph\nW. Crown for more than 33 years.\nEntered at the Post office at Berry\ntllle, Va., as second-class mail mat\nter.\n81.50 Per If car In Advance\nMILITARY PAGEANT IN\nNATION\u2019S CAPITAL SOON\nVisitors to the Nation\u2019s capital\nduring the fourth week of Septem\nber will have an opportunity to wit\nness one of the most stirring Military\nPageants that takes place in this or\nany other country, according to Col.\nLeon B. Komer, of the Army War\nCollege there.\nThe spacious grounds of the Army\nWar College, at historical Washing\nton Barracks is a most fitting setting\nfor the Annual Military Exposition\nand Carnival which will be h*V*\nSeptember 25, 26 and 27. At\nseason of the year Washington is\nmost beautiful; the weather clear,\nbracing and mellow with the rich\nness of autumn. Washington Bar\nracks borders on and is almost sur\nrounedd by the the beautl\nful Potomac.\nInauguated three years ago, the\ngerat Army show has become an an\nnual event that draws thousands of\nvisitors to Washington. It is the\noutstanding military demonstration\nthat gives to the American people an\nunderstanding of the Army\u2019s\nweapons and their employment foi\nnational defense.\nCIRCUIT COURT OPENS\nSEPTEMBER TERM MON.\nNext Monday, September 22, will\nbe court day again in Berryville\nthat being the opening day of the\nSeptember term of the Circuit Cou\nof Clarke County. Several cases^\nmostly prohibition cahrges will be\nbrought up at this time. Julge Phil p\nWilliams will preside.\nn\nFarm Sells For $23,500\nLeesburg. Va., September 12.\u2014J.\nS Heflin of Woodburn. this county,\nhas purchased the T. F. Mason farm\nconsisting of 430 acres This is one\nof the oldest estates i tnhe countiy.\nThe price paid was $23,500.\n\u25a0--O\u2014\nCARD OF THANKS\nWe wish to express our sincere\nthanks and appeeciation to our\nfriends and neighbors for their many\nexpressions of kindness and sympa\nthy in our recent bereavement. Also\nfor the use of cars and the beautiful\nfloral tributes.\nMr. and Mrs. John Shackleford.\n\u00bb\u2014--\u2014n\u2014\nCALL MEETING GOLDEN\nRULE MEMBERS TUESDAY\nA call meeting of Golden. Rule\nCircle, King\u2019s Daughters, will be\nheld in the Legion rooms next Tues\nday afternoon, September 23, at 3\no\u2019elock. All members are urged to\nattend as important business will be\n'taken up at this meeting.\n-O\nRECENT GUESTS\nAT WOODLAWN\nRecent guests registered at Wood\nlawn Tea House were Mr. and Mrs.\nFrank Woodward, Cincinnati, Ohio;\nC. B. Johnson, J. F. Kramer, Miss\nMoxine Hastin, Miss Marie'LaGue,\nSt Louis, Mo.; C. R. Rounds, Chic\nago; B. C. Siske, Warsaw, N. C.\nMr. and Mrs. George Emmerick,\nBaltimore; Miss Sarah Coe, Mrs. J\nM. Trapnell, Mrs. E. E. Cooke,\nCharles Town; Miss Mary Bolton,\nBaltimore; Mr. and Mrs. Dinges,\nBaltimore; Mr. and Mrs. H. Y.\nGeorge, Brunswick, Md.; Mr. and\nMrs. C. W. Gilbert, Miss S tella\nGrimm, Miss Polly Gilbert, Wash\nington; Mrs J. M. Lee, White Post;\nMr .and Mrs. Bruce Worthington,\nBaltimort; Miss Mary Katherine\nLutz, Miss Edith Lutz, Mr. and\nMrs. George M. Lee, Mr. and Mrs.\nJohn Lutz, Washington; Mr. and\nMrs. Frank H. Thayer, Brockton,\nMass.; Margaret M. Carson, Pitts\nburg, Pa.; Miss Mary Miller, Miss\nAnne Barton, Lewis N. Barton, Win\nchester; C. H. Arnold, S. A. Davis,\nRichmond; Mrs. Mary E. Bennett,\nBrunswick, Md.\nu\nOVER 300 SPORTSMEN\nBUY LICENSEES HERE\nThus far this season, ounty\nlicenses to hunt, fish and trap in\nClarke have been issued at the\nClerk\u2019s Office and 53 state licenses\nhave been bought. Three non-resi\ndent hunting, Ashing and trapping\nlicenses for any and all counties of\nthe state have also been bought at\nthe local office and 32 licenses to\nAsh only, in all inland waters of the\nstate have been issued to non-resi\ndents.\n-0\n15-YEAR GOITRE REMOVED\nVa. Lady Tells How In Letter Re\nceived Here.\ns Mrs. O. L. Shelton, Whittles Depot\ni Va., has written a letter to Harris\u2019\nPharmacy telling how easily she re\nI moved her goitre at home without\npain or knife. How severe choking\ndifficult breathing, throbbing, head\naches, nervousness and sleeplessness\n!j were releived. Mrs. Shelton has\nnothing to sell. You are welcome to\nH. call and read her letter \u2014Adv\na i\nPERSONALS\nMr. and Mrs. J. C. Wortman, of\nthe Modei Dairy, visited the Rich\nmond Fair last week,.\nMrs. Laura M. Jones and daugh\nter, Miss Emma Jones, of Durham,\nN. C., are visiting Mr and Mrs. Thos.\nJones and Mr. and Mrs M. W. Jones\nJr.\nMr. Joseph Jones stopped to see his\nbrother en route from Lake Placid,\nN. Y., to Chapel Hill, N. C., where.he\nis a student at the University of\nNorth Carolina\nAmong the exhibitors at the\nLoudoun County Fair and Horse\nShow this- week are Messrs. J. VV.\nBell and Thomas G. Tapscott, of\nBerryville. l\nMr. Thomas Jones attended the\nSynod of Virginia, Richmond, as a\ndelegate from the local Presbyterian\nChurch. He was accompanied by his\nlittle daughter, Elizabeth Ann, who\nvisited her aunt, Mrs. F. M. Booth.\nMaster Joseph Moore left the first\nof the week for Alexandria, where he\nwill attend Episcopal High School.\nMrs. T. W. Whitaker and Mrs. C.\nH. Iden attended the American\nLegion and Auxiliary convention in\nHarrisonburg last week.\nMr. and Mrs. T. S. Wood, of\nWashington, visited the latter's\nbrother, Mr. T. W. Whitaker.\nMr. Roy Whitaker and family of\nWaynesboro, Pa., spent Sunday with\nhis parents, Mr. and Mrs. T. W.\nWhitaker.\nBill Clagett, Walter, Wisecarver,\nJr, and Joe Galloway left yesterday\nfor Blacksburg to attend the Vir\nginia Polytechnic Institute.\nBOYCE\nMrs. Charles Adams has returned''\nfrom a visit to Pennsylvania, ac\ncompanied by her daughter, Mrs.\nHarlow.\nMr. Darvin Lubitz, of Philadel\nphia, who has been visiting in\nClarke visited at^\"The Cottage\u201d be\nfore returning. j\nThe Social Service Department of\nthe Boyce Methodist Church, will\nserve a plate chicken supper, with all\ngood tilings associated therewith, at\nthe Parish Hall at Boyce, on Septem-:\nber 19th, from 6 to 11 P. M., charge\n50i\nMiss Adelaide Elsea of Bluemont\nis spending some time with her sis-;\nter, Mrs. U. E. Smith, at Boyce.\nMr. T. A. Hooker and family, of\nBerryville were recent visitors at\nthe home of Mr. and Mrs. Robert\nPyle.\nMrs. Louise Baker DeFour and\nchildren, who have been spending.\nthe summer with Mr. and Mrs.\nGeorge Baker, at \u201cBen Lomond\u201d,\nhave returned to their home in\nSouth Carolina.\nMrs. Howard Locke and son,\nJohn Locke, visited friends in Wash\nington, D. C., last week.\nMr. Sheetz and family have re\nturned from a visit to relatives in\nPennsylvania.\nMrs. J. J. Iseman, Mrs. Reid\nStanton and little son, Billy, visited\nrelatives at Boyce last week. t\nMiss Madrid Heine has returned\nfrom a visit to Washington.\nMisses Noda Royston and Virginia\nTrenary have* entered training for\nnurses, Miss Royston at Winchester\nHospital and Miss Trenary at Emer\ngency Hospital in Washington, car-1\nrying with them the good wishes of j\na host of friends.\nMiss Susan Henderson of Caro\nline County is visiting her sister,\nMrs. Oscar Carr at \u201cSouthside\u201d.\nRev. Mr. Phillips representing\nThe Children\u2019s Home Society of\nVirginia, spoke at the Batist Church\nat 11 A. M., and at the M. E Church\nat Boyce at 8 P. M., and received a\ngenerous response to his appeal.\nDr. and Mrs. H. C. Smith, who j\nhave lately come among us, are re\nceiving a hearty welcome to the\ntown and community.\nThe Ladies Aid Society of Boyce\nBaptist. Church held the September\nmeeting on last Thursday at \u201cOak\nPark\u201d, attractive country home of\nMr. and Mrs. Clyde Levi. The at\ntendance was large and plans were\nlaid for a bazaar to be held Novem\nber 6th nd 7th. After the business\nprogram the social hour followed,\nand a most enjoyable time was spent\nby all present, cake and ice cream\nbeing served.\nMRS. BENJAMIN DIXON\nDIES AT BEDFORD HOME\nWord reached here this week of\nthe death of Mrs. Benjamin Dixon,\nwho died at her home in Bedford,\nInd., August 22, after an illness of\nsome months. She is survived by\nher husband, a 14-month old child,\none brother, Mr. Charles Thompson\nof Colorado, and a sister, Miss Edith\nThompson, of Washington, D. C.\nMrs. Dixon is known by many in\nthis community as Miss Jessie\nThompson, who spetn much time\nwith her uncle, Mr. W. M. Hardes\nty, when he lived near Crum\u2019s\nChurch. She was a granddaughter\nof the late Charles W. Hardesty.\n-O\nBAPTIST AID TO SERVE\nSUPPER NEXT THURSDAY\nThe Ladies\u2019 Aid Society of the\nBaptist Church will serve a plate\nsupper on Thursday, September 25.\nbeginning at five o\u2019clock, in the\nroom adjoining the Post Officce in\nBerryville. Price 35 cents. Every\nbody urged to come.\n-O-\u2014\nWHO OWNS THE 8TAKH?\nDid you ever stop to consider this\nmatter? Does the discoverer possess\na title to his findings? Read he in\ntensely interesting article on this\nsubject in the Magazine of The\nWashington Star for Sunday, Sep\ntember 21, ond order your copy of\nnext Sunday\u2019s Star from your' news\ndealer today.\nLOCAL RAINFALL FAR\nFROM NORMAL FOR 1930\nIt's an ill wind that blows no\nbody any good The hurricane that\nlashed Santo Domingo and then got\nlost in the ocean turned up again\nthe last of last week, and Berryville\nand Clarke County were among the\ncommunities benefiiting thereby. It\nrained here for quite a bit Saturday\nmorning, the total precipitation reg\nistering 5-16 of an inch, accoi3|ing\nto Mr. Walter Rutherford, who con\ntinues to measure the rainfall a<S his\nhome on West Main street. J.\nThis was Berryville\u2019s second *rain\nthis month, a quarter of an inch\nfalling in the previously recorded\none. Thus September has so far\naccounted for 9-16\nThe hurricane turned up the\ncoast of N. C. last Friday night and\nseemed to be progressing up the\ncoast at a rate of about 16 miles per\nhour. The wind intensity at the\nstorm scene, some miles from land,\nwas 102 miles, but it created but 5o\nor 60 miles disturbance on shore.\nAnd the wind was practically nil\nfurther inland.\nWilmington, N. C., got nearly an\ninch of rain Friday, but other areas\nonly got gentle, but welcome, show\nery\nLocal precipitation is far from\nnormal for 1930 thus far. Mr. Ruth\nerford states, after a coreful study\nof his records. But a fair average\nwould be struck if we got 8 inches\nper month from now till the end of\nthe year. This would be a comfor\ntable amount, and any more would\nbe excessive.\nIt was reported that Saturday\u2019s\nrain was heavier in the Gaylord sec\ntion.\nDINNER AT WOODLAWN\nHONOR H. OSBORNE\nDr. A. P. Osborne of \u2018\u2018Rock\ncroft\u201d was host at a dinner, Sunday\nat \u201cWoodlawn Tea House\u201d, in hon\nor of his son, Mr. Hunter Osborne,\nwho recently returned from Texas.\nDr. Osborne\u2019s guests were Messrs.\nH. F. Byrd, Hunter Osborne, J. F.\nSpates, Blackburn Moore, Ralph\nDorsey, W. A. Daniels, Thomas\nElsea, L. X. Glover, H. B. Harris,\nHobson MeGehee and J. D. Griffing\nof Berryville, Arthur Glover, of\nCharles Town, H. T. Plaster, of\nWashington, and Arthur Chichester\nand John Gallagher, of Leesburg.\nMr. Osborne left Sunday night for\nNew Jersey, where he will be man\naging editor of a chain of papers.\n_0\nMISS LLOYD WED IN\nWASHINGTON MONDAY\nMr. and Mrs. O. A. Lloyd have\nannounced the marriage of their\ndaughter, Miss Edith Grey Lloyd, to\nMr. Edward L. Moyer, of Washing\nton, on Monday, September 15. The\nceremony was performed by the\nRev. J. G. Johnson at the National.\nMemorial Baptist Church in Wash\nington.\nMr. Moyer, a son of Mr? and\nMrs. C. L. Moyer, of Leesburg,\nVa., has been employed for some\nyears in Washington.\nAfter a short trip south, Mr. and\nMrs. Moyer will be at home at 1466\nColumbia Road, Washington, D. C.\n-II\nKERCHEVAL POLICING\nFOR BERRYVILLE NOW\nSergeant William Levi, who was\nconfined to his home last week, is\nable to be out again, but will not re\nturn to his post until he has com\npletely recovered. Mr. John Ker\ncheval, member of the local unit of\nthe Virginia National Guards is now\npolicing for Berryville. He relieved\nCorporal Mat Pulliam last Thursday\nwhen he left to take up his studies\nat the Richmond Medical College.\n-O\nHAWTHORNE JUNIORS\nREORGANIZE LEAGUE\nThe Junior League of Hawthorne\nSchool was reorganized with the\nfollowing officers: Margaret Myers,\npresident; Evelyn Bryant, vice-pres\nident; Elizabeth Locke, secretary;\nWalter Myers, treasurer; outside\nhealth monitors, Wm. Atehy, John\nMyers, Walter Shepherd; inside\nhealth monitors, Lola Taylor, Louise\nBarritt, Garret Shepherd; librarian,\nBertha Shepherd.\nSome needed supplies are being\nbought for the school and the Lea\ngue is considering a flag pole to be\nerected on the school ground. They\nare also going to have a \u201cClean-no\nDay\u201d, this week and prospects are\nfor a bright school year, starting\nout with twenty-five pupils oif roll\nat present.\nATTEND PRESBYTERIAN\nSYNOD IN RICHMOND\nRev. James McL. Carr and Mr.\nThomas Jones, of the Berryville\nPresbyterian Church, attended the\nPresbyterian Synod of Virginia which\nmet at Union Theological Seminary,\nin Richmond last week. The open*\ning sermon was preached by the re\ntiring moderator, Rev. Dr. Thornton\nS. Wilson, of Halifax county\nRev. Charles R. Stribling, pastor\nof the church at Orangt, was elected\nmoderator for the next term, while\nthe Rev* C. R. Bailey, of Ronce- 1\nverte, W. Va., was chosen reading I\nclerk.\nDr. Wilson said in his sermon,\nwhich was based on John 20:19-25.\nin speaking of the duty and power of\nI the Church in the present times, \u201cIt\n1 is the duty of the Church to answer i\nthe quest of the world, which is say\ning, \u2018We would see Jesus.\u2019 The home\nj has passed, the Sabbath is dtsecrated\nand crime is ^weeping the world. The\npower of the Church is needed and\nall power is given to it. The discip\nles felt their inability. The Church\nfeels its inability today. But through\nChrist the disciples became powerful\nin their work The Church, todfly has\nthe same Gospel, the same world in\nneed of the same Saviour. It\u2019s duty,\nprivilege and power is to carry this\nGospel to every creature.\u201d 1\nFollowing the various reports and\naddresses it was decided that the\nnext meeting of the Synod will be\nheld on September 8, 1931. The place\nof meeting Was left to the moderatoi\nand state clerk^ provided some\nchurch invites the Synod to meet\nwith it If no such invitation is re\nceived the meeting will be held agai\nat Union Theological Seminary, a?\nthis year.\nLAND POSTED\nMrs. C. C. Lewis, \u2018\u2018Fielding'\u2019.\n-O--V\nPUBLIC SALE\nj\nOF HOUSE AND LOT\nI By virtue of the authority granted\nme by a certain decree of the Cir\ncuit Court of Clarke County, Vir\nginia, entered in the Chancery\ncause of the Valley Motor Company.\nG. E. Lemley, Proprietor, vs. Al\nfred Bray ,et als, now pending in the\nsaid Court. I will offer for sale at\npublic auction to the highest bidder\nIn front of the Court House at Ber\nryville, Virginia, on\nTHURSDAY, OCTOBER 16th.\nI At Eleven O\u2019clock A. M.\nAll o fthat certain real estate be\nlonging to Alfred Bray, consisting\nof two (2) acres, more or less, and\nimproved by a good dwelling house\nand other outbuildings, situaaed\nnear Millwood, on the State High\nway leading from Berryville to Mill\nwood\nTERMS OP SALE\nThis sale will be for one-half cash\non day of sale, and the balance evi\ndenced by the notes of the purchaser\nin equal amounts, payable one and\ntwo years after date, and secured by\na deed of trust constituting a first\nlien on the property, together with\nI a fire insurance policy on the build\nj ings, or the purchaser may pay all\njcash on day of sale.\nj FRANK M WRAY,\nSpecial Commissioner\n9-18 4t\nIX THE UNITED STATES IMS-1\nTIUCT COURT FOR THE WEST- I\nTERN DISTRICT OF VIRGINIA\nIn tin* Matter of\nMrs. Edna L. Young\nBankrupt.\nIn Bankruptcy No. 7!2U\nTo the creditors of Mrs. Edna L.\nYoung, of Berryville, Glarke Coun\nty, Virginia:\ni NOTICE is hereby given that on\nthe 8th day of September, 1930\nMrs. Edna L. Young was duly ad\njudicated bankrupt, and the first\nmeeting of her creditors will be held\nat the office of Frank M. Wray, ir\nj the city of Berryville, Virginia, oi:\ntlie 24th day of September, 1930, at\n12:00 o\u2019clock M, at which time said\n1 creditors may attend, prove then\nclaims, examine the bankrupt, ap\npoint -a Trustee if necessary, and\ntransact such other business as ma>\nproperly come before said meeting.\nDated, Harrisonburg, Virginia\nSeptember 10, 1930.\nEDWART C. MARTZ,\nReferee in Bankruptcy\nIt pd.\nTEN YEARS AGO\nTHE BUSINESS OUTLOOK mt poor\nthe markets were erratic and unemploy\nment was bn the increase. At that time\nour advice was to avoid becoming pani\ncky, to work and to save, looking forward\nto the inevitable readjustment that must\nfollow.\nTODAY our advice is the same.\nS\n\n\u25a0f 4-i\nS\nTHE\n\u201e.-i\u2018\nFirst National Bank\nof Berryville\nCONSULT US ABOUT YOUR\nBUILDING MATERIALS\nYellow Pine and Fir Framing and Sheathing\nPine and Fir Flooring Rift and Flat\nLong Bell Oak Flooring\nHigh Grade Finish Lumber\nU. S. Gypsum Plaster and Stucco\nMorgan Millwork\nWeather Best Stained Shingles\nJohns Manville Roofing Rigid Asbestos\nand Flexible Asphalt\nSand and Stone\nLehigh and Atlas Portland Cement\nRussell and Erwin Hardware\ndu Pont Paints and Varnishes\nWe shall be glad to give you an estimate\non your work\nJob W. Rosenberger Company\nPhone 72 Winchester, Virginia\n24 Hour\nMessenger\nP GJorSales\nHEN you want to go to\nthe store... or call a taxi... or\ninvite someone over... or talk\nwith a sick friend... or send a\ntelegram or just talk for\ntalk's sake... call on that tire\nless messenger THE TELE\nPHONE-IF YOU HAVE ONE!\nIf not\u2014well, just call our Busi\nness Office, or stop one of our\nemployees on the street, and\nwe will put one in for you in\nshort order. It only costs a\nfew cents a day.\nTHE CHESAPEAKE AND POTOMAC TELEPHONE COMPANY\nOF VIRGINIA\n\u201cON THE KORNER\u201d\nSCHOOL DAYS ARE HERE AGAIN\nWe Have A Full Line Of N\nTablets, Pencils, Notebooks Pens and Ink\n\u201cYou jes oughter see our Amos *n Andy\nTablets\u201d\nWyndham Supply Store\nH. B. WYNDHAM, Prop.","height":"29792","width":"20728"}}
